    <section name="Windows Setup Options">
      <p>This section details a couple of options for setting up a Windows environment for launching the Generate Tool.
      </p>

      <subsection name="Specify the CLASSPATH on the Command-Line">
        <p>An alternative method to setting the <i>CLASSPATH</i> variable with all of the tool's dependent JAR files is to specify the <i>java.ext.dirs</i> Java property on the command-line when running the tool each time. This is done by passing the property via the Java "-D" flag as demonstrated in the following example:
        </p>

        <source>
C:\&gt; java -Djava.ext.dirs=c:\\${xdoc-artifactId}-${xdoc-version}\lib \
gov.nasa.pds.validate.ValidateLauncher \
&lt;targets&gt; &lt;command-line arguments&gt;
        </source>
      </subsection>

      <subsection name="Specify the JAR on the Command-Line">
        <p>Another alternative method is to specify the executable JAR file on the command-line when running the tool each time. This is done by passing the JAR file specification via the Java "-jar" flag as demonstrated in the following example:
        </p>

        <source>
C:\&gt; java -jar c:\\${xdoc-artifactId}-${xdoc-version}\lib\\${xdoc-artifactId}-${xdoc-version}.jar \
&lt;targets&gt; &lt;command-line arguments&gt;
        </source>
      </subsection>

      <subsection name="Specify the Path in the Control Panel">
        <p>The method for setting the executable path permanently for Harvest Tool is to set the <i>Path</i> environment variable via the control panel as follows:
        </p>

        <ul>
          <li>Right-click on <i>My Computer</i> icon on your desktop and select the <i>Properties</i> menu item.
          </li>
          <li>Navigate to the <i>Advanced</i> tab and select the <i>Environment Variables</i> button. At this point, you should now see a window like the one below:
          </li>
        </ul>

        <center><img src="../images/windows_panel.jpg"/></center>

        <ul>
          <li>Highlight the <i>Path</i> variable in the System Variables list and select the Edit button.
          </li>
          <li>Append to the current contents of the variable, the path to the <i>bin</i> directory within <i>${xdoc-artifactId}</i> package. Separate the package path from the current contents of the variable with a semicolon.
          </li>
          <li>Select the <i>OK</i> button when you are finished editing the <i>Path</i> variable, then select the <i>OK</i> button at the Environment Variables window to apply the changes.
          </li>
        </ul>

        <p>Note: If you already have a DOS window open, you will need to close and re-open the window for the <i>Path</i> changes to take effect.
        </p>
      </subsection>
    </section>
